<h3 id="abs" class="level2">UV/Vis Absorption spectroscopy (ABS)</h3>
<p class="item">
  Absorption spectroscopy is a widely used technique in analytical chemistry which uses the wavelength dependent absorption characteristics of materials to identify and quantify specific substances.
</p>
<p class="item">
  The absorption of a photon leads to the transition of an electron from the ground state (S<sub>0</sub>) to an excited state (S<sub>x</sub>
  with x>0), see
  <a href="#f7">Jablonski diagram</a>. The wavelength of the absorbed photon is hereby dependent on the energy gap between S<sub>x</sub>
  and S<sub>0</sub>. If the energy gap is small, light having a small energy and, thus, a long wavelength is absorbed.
</p>
<p class="item">
  Employing Lambert-Beer’s law, the
  <b>absorbance A</b>
  of a molecule can be used to determine its concentration in the measured solution as the law states that the absorbance A is directly proportional to the concentration c of the absorbing species.<a href="#Tec_ref">
    <sup>[7,11]</sup>
  </a>
  The absorbance A is a dimensionless quantity and is the degree of the light intensity reduction after crossing a certain matter
  <em>
    e.g.</em>
  the sample cell:
