<p class="item">
  Absorption spectroscopy is commonly used to examine the binding affinities of two molecules to each other (<em>e.g.</em>
  host-guest complexes), by measuring the absorbance of the formed complex during the titration of one species to the other. Here, often the host is added stepwise to a guest solution and the absorbance is measured after each addition. The
  <a href="TD_Ka">binding affinity <em>K</em><sub>a</sub></a> can then be determined by fitting the curve of the obtained data points (absorbance vs. concentration of the host) (see
  <a href="#f9">
    Figure 9</a>).
  <a href="#Tec_ref">
    <sup>[12]</sup>
  </a>
</p>

